Introduction¶

The dataset we are going to use for analysis comes form four csv files contained in the database_soccer folder, Country ,Leagues ,Matchs and Teams all combined in one dataframe matches_df through many steps bellow, and in which we find :

  • 11 european countries along with their 11 championship 
  • the names of all teams competitors for all 11 countries
  • the stage represents the order of the week (generally 34) in the year in which each team play one match
  • the date of each match of all seasons and the season (the year) from 2008 to 2016
  • the result of each match with the number of goals of both home and away team

The purpose is trying to answer the following questions :

  1. Which league/country has the most goals in the first 3 stages of the season, and for the first three season from 2008 to 2010 ?
  2. How does the average goal scored in each league evolve in the seasons 2008/2009 , 2010/2011 and 2014/2015?

The Total Goals in The First Three Seasons/Stages¶

Our purpose is to answer the first question which is trying to find the league/country that has the most goals in the first 3 stages of the season and for the first three season from 2008 to 2010 , as first step we add a column to our datafrrame containing the total number of goals scored each match , then we filter our dataframe:

In [79]:
# First of all we add a new column to our dataset contains the total number of goals
matches_df['total_goals'] = matches_df['home_team_goal']+matches_df['away_team_goal']

Evolution of The Average of Goals Scored in Each League¶

In order to answer the second question which consist of the evolution of the average goals scored in seasons : 2008/2009 , 2010/2011 and 2014/2015, for the first step we groupby season and league name and calculating the mean for each season and each league:

In [85]:
# We are going to groupby season and league name 
SandL_groupby_df = matches_df.groupby(['season','league_name']).mean()
SandL_groupby_df.head()

# Now we are setting up a function that will plot the league names as horizontal bars, with the season given as an argument
def func_plot_bar(S):
    SandL_groupby_df.loc[S]['total_goals'].plot(kind='barh',figsize=(10,5))
    plt.title('Average number of goals scored in season for all leagues')
    plt.xlabel(f'{S} Season')
    plt.ylabel('Average number of goals');

From the graphs above we can see that the gap between leagues in the average score is getting smaller in those three seasons, to see this more clearly, we are going to plot lines:

In [93]:
# We use this function to plot a line graph for each desired season as an argument
def func_plot_line(S):
    plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 25})
    plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = [30,15]
    plt.title(f'Average number of goals in each league for the {S} season')
    plt.plot(SandL_groupby_df.loc[S].index,SandL_groupby_df.loc[S]['total_goals'])
    plt.xticks(SandL_groupby_df.loc[S].index)
    plt.xticks(rotation='vertical')
    plt.xlabel(f'{S} Season')
    plt.ylabel('Average number of goals');
In [94]:
func_plot_line('2008/2009')
In [92]:
func_plot_line('2010/2011')
In [53]:
func_plot_line('2014/2015')

Hence we notice that the line graph becomes more and more stable, from the first to the third season in question, in other words the dispertion around the average of averages is decreasing from the first to the last season shown , and we could check this by calculating the standard deviation for each season and see if it gets smaller:

In [123]:
def std_calculator(S):
    df.loc[S]['total_goals'].std()

Conclusions¶

To resume our findings in this analysis for both questions we conclude that:

  • In the first question we try to find the league/country that has the most goals in the first 3 stages of the season and for the first three season from 2008 to 2010, we used our cleaned dataframe matches_df after that we add a column containing the total number of goals, then we filter the dataframe using query method twice to get only desired stages and seasons, and as a final step we groupby league/country name and calculate the sum of total goals, just to find after checking that the England Premier League is the correct answer to our question.
  • For the second question, we want to know more about the evolution of the average goals scored in seasons : 2008/2009 , 2010/2011 and 2014/2015, so we take the first step which is groupby season and league name and calculating the mean for each season and each league, then we use the first function to plot horizontal bars with league names shown clearly for desired season, after we use a second function to plot line graphs to check more if the difference between leagues in term of average goals scored per season is becoming smaller, which means that the dispertion around the average of averages(for each league) is is decreasing ,and to verify that claim we calculate the standard deviation and we found that is true.

The Limitations are generally two:

  • The first is the multi sources of the dataset as it comes from four csv files but originally it was one database in the form of SQLite file, hence I have been in several problems when I tried to join multiple tables into one, SQLite DB manager doesn't support full join as far as i can tell, hence I have to do it with pandas methods which will not seve us in the case of a large database.
  • The second is in the graphs when I use plt.plot method in the line graphs since I could also use pd.plot method, but i came across problem of not showing x labels (names of leagues), thus I use plt.plot as a replacement.
